pretty_estimates <- function(m) { # m: model object
    cbind(Est. = m$coefficients, confint(m))
}

The F test has a p-value of 0.09 so not significant difference, but would you really rule it out entirely? Also because the p values for the coefficients from the two exposure groups are actually below 0.05. Its important, however, to note that the CIs for these confidence intervals are basically 0 to 1, so quite imprecise.

If we want to study the pairwise differences, we have to use Tukey-corrected T tests. That requires an analysis-of-variance, and running the Tukey multiple comparisons of means analysis we see that all CIs contain 0 (although not by a large margin for short vs.long exposure and no vs.long exposure, which corresponds well to what we saw in the boxplots). Also note that the CIs are now wider because weve corrected for multiple comparisons.

model2 <- aov(vitcap ~ grp, data = cad)
TukeyHSD(model2)

Q4: Correlation between vitcap and age within each group

Ill do linear model instead of correlation test per se. The regression coefficients within each group might sugggest that vital capacity fall more rapidly in the long-term exposed individuals. Inteterstingly, the long-term exposed have higher vitcap when younger. Not also that ggplot2 doesnt extrapolate the lines beyond the data, as base graphics in R do.

Q6: Provide estimate for the difference between 40-year old long-term exposed individuals and 40-year old non-exposed

We need a combined model (of course). From the ANOVA we see that there are differences in vitcap for 40-year old individuals across the groups (p = 0.034), but we dont know how. The difference between the two groups can not be read directly from the coefficients (between we centered age at 40 years), and suggests that long-term exposure is favourable to non-exposure (negative coefficient for being non-exposed); it isnt significant, though. When looking at the plot above, we can also see that making statements on 40-year old long-term exposued individuals is a bit sketchy as we are at the bound of the data.

cad <- mutate(cad, age_around_40 = age - 40)

To visualise these parallel lines, we now have to make predictions and show those as a line:

preds <- expand.grid(sex = c("Female", "Male"), age = 0:13, stringsAsFactors = FALSE) %>% 
    bind_cols(pred = predict(ancova, .))

ggplot(mapping = aes(x = age, colour = sex)) +
    geom_point(aes(y = log_sigf1), filter(juul, tanner == 1)) +
    geom_line(aes(y = pred), preds)

Q3: Why would linear regression be inappropraite for all Tanner groups?

Just show the scatter plots and a smooth line; its in no way straight.

select(juul, log_sigf1, age, sex) %>% 
    na.exclude() %>% 
    ggplot(aes(age, log_sigf1)) +
        geom_point() +
        geom_smooth() +
        facet_wrap(~ sex)

Q4: Consider only post-pubertal

For males, linear effect seems plausible but definitely not for women.

Fit model with interaktion as the lines do not seem parallel. The interaction term however is far from significant, and the effect is near-zero.

Always look at the missigness pattern! Note that I transpose it, as I find it to give a more intuitive output. 1s mean observed value, 0s mean missing value. Column titles indicate the number of patients with the pattern in that column. The bottom row shows the total number of variables with missing values in that column. The right-most column shows the number of patients with missing values for each variable. This is not the case for the plot which is in the original direction.

library(mice)
t(md.pattern(juul, rotate.names = TRUE))
